Tacitus, with all his partiality for German manners and moi-als, still retains the heart of a Roman patriot. He loves his country with all her faultS, and bears no good-will to her enemies, however many and great their virtues. The passage is important, as illus- trating the spirit and design of the whole Treatise. The work was not written as a blind panegyrie on the Germans, or a spleeny satire on the Romans. Neither was it composed for the purpose of stirring up Trajan to war against Germany; to such a purpose, such a clause, as umentibus imperii fatie, were quite adverse. Least of all was it written for the mere pastime and amusement of Roman readers. It breathes the spirit at once of the earnest patriot, and the high· -toned moralist.
